				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F_M\left( x \right) = \mathop {\sum}\limits_{m = 1}^M {T\left( {x,\theta _m} \right)},$$\end{document}where m is the times of training, x is the input data, and θm is the distribution weight vector. The model is trained M times, and each time it produces a weak regression function T. The loss function of every weak classifier, is defined as2θ̂m= arg minθm ∑i=1NLyi,Fm-1xi+Txi,θm,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hat \theta _{m} = \mathop{\arg \hskip 2pt \min}\limits_{\theta _m}\mathop {\sum}\limits_{i = 1}^{N} L \left({y_{i},F_{m - 1}\left( {x_i} \right) + T\left( {x_{i},\theta _{m}} \right)} \right),$$\end{document}where Fm-1(xi) is the current model, and GBR determines the parameters of the next weak classifier through empirical risk minimization. This work uses ML to analyze a small dataset based on DFT calculation to construct a predictive model.
